ink to be built to Wairere Drive/Gordonton Road/Crosby Road roundabout\n|-style=\"background:#FFDEAD;\"\n| \n| \n|\n| {{jct|country=NZL|SH|26|name1=Ruakura Link}} \u2013 [[University of Waikato|University]], Hamilton Central, [[Morrinsville]]\n| Link to be built east to Ruakura Road and west to Ruakura Road/Silverdale Road roundabout<br> SH 26 to be diverted via Ruakura Road to meet interchange.\n|-style=\"background:#FFDEAD;\" \n| \n| \n|\n| Cambridge Road \u2013 Hillcrest, Hamilton Central\n| \n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=center| ''Currently terminates at Bollard Road''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| Waikato District\n| rowspan=2| Tamahere\n| 560.4\n|\n| {{jct|country=NZL|SH|21}} \u2013 [[Tamahere]], [[Hamilton Airport (New Zealand)|Hamilton Airport]]\n| {{coord|-37.82829|175.35760|format=dms|name=SH 21 interchange|type:landmark_region:NZ-WKO|display=inline}} \n|-\n|-\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Waipa District]]\n| \n|\n| Cambridge Road \u2013 [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]] (west)\n| Northbound entrance and southbound exit\n|-\n| rowspan=3| Cambridge\n|\n|\n| {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1B|name1=Victoria Road}} \u2013 Cambridge, Hautapu\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n| Tirau Road (north)\u2013 Cambridge\n| Northbound exit and southbound entrance \n|-\n|\n|\n| {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|name1=Tirau Road|dir1=south}} \u2013 [[Rotorua]], [[Taupo]]\n| ''Waikato Expressway ends''<br />{{coord|-37.8967|175.50796|format=dms|name=End of Waikato Expressway|type:landmark_region:NZ-WKO|display=inline}} \n|}\n\n===Mangaharakeke Drive (Te Rapa spur)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Territorial authority]] \n! Location\n! [[Exit number|Exit]]\n! Destination\n! Notes\n|- \n| rowspan=2| Waikato District\n| rowspan=2| Horsham Downs\n|\n| [[File:State Highway 1 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 1|SH 1]] Waikato Expressway north <br> [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]], [[Auckland]]\n| ''Mangaharakeke Drive begins'' <br> No east to south connection <br> \n|-style=\"background:#FFDEAD;\" \n|\n| Lake Road\n| Northbound exit only <br> to Waikato Expressway southbound (future)\n|- style=\n| rowspan=2| Waikato District\u2013Hamilton City boundary\n| Horotiu\n|\n| Great South Road/Te Rapa Road \u2013 [[Te Rapa]], Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia\n|Crosses [[Waikato River]] on [[Horotiu#2013 Waikato Expressway bridge|Te Rehu O Waikato Bridge]]\n|- \n| Burbush\n|\n| {{jct|country=NZL|SH|39|name1=Koura Drive}} \u2013 [[Raglan, New Zealand|Raglan]], [[Otorohanga]]\n| \n|- \n| rowspan=2| [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton City]]\n| rowspan=2| Avalon\n| \n| Wairere Drive/Te Wetini Drive\n| Southbound exit and northbound entrance\n|- \n|\n| Avalon Drive\n| ''Mangaharakeke Drive ends''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of motorways and expressways in New Zealand]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/index.html Official website]\n*[http://www.fletcherconstruction.co.nz/news/2017/september-2017/biggest-roading-project-in-hamilton video of 10 min flyover of Hamilton bypass route in September 2017]\n\n{{New Zealand motorway list}}\n\n[[Category:Roads in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Transport in Waikato]]\n[[Category:New Zealand State Highway 1]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2015}}\n{{infobox road\n|country=NZL\n|type=SH\n|route=1\n|name= Waikato Expressway\n|alternate_name= [[New Zealand State Highway 1|State Highway 1]]\n|map= \n|map_notes= \n|length_km= 93.2\n|direction_a= North\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_a= [[Bombay Hills]]<br>[[Auckland Southern Motorway]]\n|destinations=[[Pokeno]], Mercer, [[Meremere]], [[Te Kauwhata|Te&nbsp;Kauwhata]], [[Rangiriri]]\n|terminus_b=Just south of [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]]\n|formed= 8 May 1993\n|history=Under construction\n|junction= [[File:State Highway 2 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 2|SH 2]] at Pokeno<br />[[File:State Highway 1b NZ.svg|20px]] SH 1B at Taupiri<br />[[File:State Highway 21 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 21|SH 21]] at Tamahere<br />[[File:State Highway 1b NZ.svg|20px]] SH 1B at Cambridge\n}}\n\nThe '''Waikato Expressway''' is a [[dual carriageway]] section of [[New Zealand State Highway 1|State Highway 1]] in the [[Waikato]] region of the [[North Island]] of New Zealand that is being constructed in stages. It forms part of the link between [[Auckland]] and [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]. When completed it will stretch {{Convert|116|km||abbr=on}} and be {{Convert|6|km||abbr=on}} shorter than the roads it replaced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsp-opus.co.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/|title=Waikato Expressway|website=www.wsp-opus.co.nz|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, the expressway is made up of two sections: the first beginning at the end of the [[Auckland Southern Motorway]] at the top of the [[Bombay Hills]] and ending at Te Rapa and the second beginning at Tamahere and ending 2.5&nbsp;km south of [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]]. When completed, the expressway will form a 101.4&nbsp;km long continuous four-lane dual carriageway from the Bombay Hills to beyond the town of Cambridge, 24 kilometres south-east of Hamilton. Hamilton, as well as several other towns along the current route of State Highway 1  (such as [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]], [[Ngaruawahia]] and Cambridge), will be completely bypassed by the expressway, allowing through traffic to move much more efficiently.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nzta.govt.nz/network/projects/project.html?ID=63 |title=Waikato Expressway |work=[[NZ Transport Agency]] |date=2009|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhile not officially designated as the Waikato Expressway until the early 2000s, the upgrading of State Highway 1 from the Bombay Hills to Mercer from 1992 to 1993 can be considered to be the first step in the construction of the expressway. During this upgrade, State Highway 1 from the end of the Southern Motorway to just north of Mercer was upgraded from two lanes to four, with grade separated interchanges constructed at Bombay and the junction with State Highway 2 just north of the township of [[Pokeno]]. A bypass of Pokeno was also constructed at this time, as well as several partially separated interchanges to allow access for local property owners along the route.<ref name=\"Auckland Motorways 2008\">{{cite web|title=Auckland Motorways 2008|url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/resources/auckland-motorways/docs/2008.pdf|publisher=New Zealand Transport Agency|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Rangiriri to Ohinewai section was completed in 2003. The northern half of this section follows the pre-existing highway while the southern half of this section deviates from the original highway in order to bypass Ohinewai and features a diamond interchange on Tahuna Rd.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangiriri to South of Ohinewai|url=http://sh20mountroskill.co.nz/projects/waikatoexpressway/about/rangiriri.jsp|work=Waikato Expressway|publisher=Transit New Zealand|accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Mercer to Longswamp section from the Bombay Hills to Mercer was opened in July 2006. The former two-lane section of State Highway is now the carriageway for northbound traffic, while a separate carriageway for southbound traffic was constructed in parallel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Traffic switches to new lanes at Mercer|url=http://sh20mountroskill.co.nz/projects/waikatoexpressway/news/003.jsp|accessdate=23 January 2012|newspaper=Transit New Zealand Press release|date=22 April 2004}}</ref>  A grade-separated interchange at Mercer was also constructed, incorporating an overpass for the southbound lanes to cross over the [[North Island Main Trunk]] railway at this point.\n\nAs the two dual carriageway sections of the expressway (Bombay Hills to Longswamp and Rangiriri to Ohinewai) are not continuous, the section of highway between Longswamp and Rangiriri was upgraded to a [[2+1 road]] in 2005 with the intention of upgrading this section to four lanes in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Longswamp to Te Kauwhata Four-Laning|url=http://sh20mountroskill.co.nz/projects/waikatoexpressway/about/longswamp.jsp|work=Waikato Expressway|publisher=Transit New Zealand|accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the Waikato Expressway was announced by New Zealand's minister of Transport, [[Steven Joyce]], as being one of seven \"roads of national significance\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Roads of national significance |url= http://www.nzta.govt.nz/network/rons/index.html |publisher=NZ Transport Agency |accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Mangaharakeke Drive section, originally known as the Te Rapa Bypass, was opened on 3 December 2012 between [[Horotiu, Waikato#Bridges|Horotiu]] and Rotokauri.<ref>{{cite web|title=New length of Waikato Expressway now open to traffic|url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/about/media/releases/2329/news.html|work=www.nzta.govt.nz|publisher=New Zealand Transport Agency|accessdate=11 December 2012|date=3 December 2012}}</ref> Construction of the section of the expressway and Mangaharakeke Drive between Taupiri and Horotiu, bypassing Ngaruawahia, began in late 2011 and was officially opened on 14 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Waikato Expressway contract awarded |url= http://www.nzta.govt.nz/about/media/releases/1148/news.html |publisher=NZ Transport Agency |accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing funding approval in December 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Construction funding approved for two sections of the Waikato Expressway|url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/traffic/current-conditions/bulletin/2359/news.html|publisher=NZTA|accessdate=19 December 2012|date=18 December 2012}}</ref> construction of the Rangiriri and Cambridge sections commenced in 2013, in March and August respectively. The Cambridge section was officially opened on 15 December 2015 by Transport Minister [[Simon Bridges]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Associate Minister marks start of Waikato Expressway \u2013 Rangiriri|url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/about/media/releases/2466/news.html|work=Waikato Expressway|publisher=New Zealand Transport Agency: Waikato Regional Office|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=Cambridge>{{cite news|last=Henson|first=Narelle|title=$250m project brings bypass, bridges and 300 jobs|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/9109636/250m-project-brings-bypass-bridges-and-300-jobs|accessdate=13 December 2013|newspaper=Waikato Times|date=31 August 2013}}</ref> with the road opening to traffic the next day.\n\nThe Rangiriri section mainline opened as a single carriageway on 21 June 2016,<ref name=\"Rangiriri\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/80803689/rangiriri-section-of-waikato-expressway-set-to-open |title=Rangiriri section of Waikato Expressway set to open |work=Waikato Times |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=7 June 2016 |accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> and became fully operational as a dual carriageway on 13 April 2017.\n\nConstruction of the Huntly section began in late August 2015. Construction of the biggest section, the Hamilton section, commenced in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/77785590/pm-and-transport-minister-turn-sod-on-hamilton-section-of-waikato-expressway |title=PM and Transport Minister turn sod on Hamilton section of Waikato Expressway |newspaper=Waikato Times |date=11 March 2016}}</ref> Construction for the Longswamp section, the last section to commence, began in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/82013876/Contract-awarded-for-final-part-of-Waikato-Expressway |title=Contract awarded for final part of Waikato Expressway |work=Waikato Times |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=12 July 2016 |accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> It was opened in December 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2019/12/waikato-expressway-longswamp-section-finally-opening-for-christmas-commuters.html |title=Waikato Expressway: Longswamp section finally opening for Christmas motorists |work=Newshub |author=Jamie Ensor |date=18 December 2019 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the NZTA started consulting on a 16&nbsp;km extension of the expressway, from the current terminus at Cambridge south to the [[New Zealand State Highway 29|SH 29]] intersection at [[Piarere]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/92059015/new-road-to-improve-link-between-hamilton-and-tauranga|title=Tauranga turnoff 'black spot' to benefit from proposed expressway extension: Government|publisher=stuff.co.nz|date=1 May 2017|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Cambridge section became one of the first two sections of highway in New Zealand to be given a speed limit of 110 km/h.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/motoring/news/99722452/waikato-tauranga-expressway-speed-limits-to-rise-to-110kh |title=Waikato, Tauranga expressway speed limits rise to 110kmh |author=Phillipa Yalden |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=11 December 2017 |accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Section\n! Location\n! Length\n! Cost\n! Constructed\n! Note\n|-\n| Pokeno\n| Bombay\u2013Mercer\n| 12&nbsp;km\n| \n| \u22121995\n|\n|- \n| Mercer\n| Mercer\u2013Hampton Downs\n| 11&nbsp;km\n| $83.5m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Opening of SH1 Mercer to Longswamp|url = http://www.beehive.govt.nz/node/26625|website = The Beehive|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| \u22122006\n| \n|-\n| Longswamp\n| Hampton Downs\u2013Te Kauwhata\n| 6&nbsp;km\n| $115m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Longswamp  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/longswamp/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\t\t\n| 2016\u20132019\n|\n|- \n| Rangiriri\n| Te Kauwhata\u2013Ohinewai\n| 5&nbsp;km\n| $105m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Rangiriri  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/rangiriri/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2013\u20132017\n|\n|-\n| Ohinewai\n| Ohinewai bypass\n| 7&nbsp;km\n| $24m<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hardingconsultants.co.nz/ipenz2011/downloads/Daniel__Grant.pdf|title = SH16 Hobsonville Deviation and SH16 Brigham Creek Extension|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |page = 4 Table 1}}</ref>\n| \u22122003\n|\n|-\n| Huntly\n| Ohinewai\u2013Taupiri\n| 15&nbsp;km\n| $458m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Huntly  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/huntly/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2015\u20132020\n| Opened March 2020. New highway bypassing Huntly<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/120120503/huntly-section-of-waikato-expressway-open-to-traffic |title=Huntly section of Waikato Expressway open to traffic |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ngaruawahia\n| Taupiri\u2013Horotiu\n| 7&nbsp;km\n| $190m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/ngaruawahia/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2011\u20132013\n| Opened December 2013. New highway bypassing Ngaruawahia.\n|-\n| Te Rapa\n| Horotiu\u2013Rotokauri\n| 10&nbsp;km\n| $195m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Te Rapa  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/te-rapa/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2010\u20132012\n| Opened December 2012. New highway bypassing Te Rapa.\n|-style=\"background:#FFDEAD;\"\n| Hamilton\n| Lake Road interchange\u2013Tamahere\n| 22&nbsp;km\n| $973m<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/media-releases/largest-roading-project-in-the-waikatos-history-to-get-underway-this-month |title=Largest roading project in the Waikato\u2019s history to get underway this month |work=NZ Transport Agency |date=11 March 2016 |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Hamilton  {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/hamilton/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2016\u20132021\n| \n|-\n| Tamahere\n| Tamahere bypass\n| 2&nbsp;km\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| Cambridge\n| Tamahere\u2013Cambridge south\n| 16&nbsp;km\n| $250m<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cambridge   {{!}} NZ Transport Agency|url = https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/waikato-expressway/cambridge/|website = www.nzta.govt.nz|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>\n| 2013\u20132015\n| Opened 16 December 2015. Upgraded highway from Tamahere to Cambridge north; new highway bypassing Cambridge\n|}\n\n==Safety==\nOn the 16km Cambridge section in the year following its opening, up to 50 serious crashes were avoided because of road safety barriers.<ref>{{cite web |title= No fatalities all year on Expressway with new barriers |url= https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/320635/no-fatalities-all-year-on-expressway-with-new-barriers/ |date= 17 December 2016 |publisher= RNZ}}</ref>\n\n==Economic benefits==\nA 2009 report for [[NZ Transport Agency|New Zealand Transport Agency]] (NZTA) concluded that the [[Benefit\u2013cost ratio|benefit cost ratio]] of the Expressway was 0.5, i.e. for every dollar of investment the return was 50 cents.<ref>[http://transportblog.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/saha-assessment.pdf New Zealand Transport Agency \u2013 Roads of National Significance \u2013 Economic Assessments 2009 p. 33]</ref>\n\nThe figures were reworked in 2010 because \"Infometrics original RoNS analysis and report was concluded in December 2009. Since this time, NZTA published an updated conventional evaluation of the Waikato Expressway. The materiality of the change to the Waikato Expressway assessment warranted an update and re-run of the CGE model.\" The re-run model shows benefits of $186.3m pa, against annual costs of $87.3m. However, this is based on a total cost for the road of $1454.4m, which omits land costs, \"as from an economy-wide perspective this is merely a transfer of ownership of an existing asset\".<ref>[http://www.nzta.govt.nz/resources/rons-economic-assessment-2010-05/docs/full-report.pdf Roads of National Significance, Economic Assessments Review 2010]</ref> In June 2015 the NZTA estimated the total cost of the road at between $2,200m and $2,400m.<ref>[http://hamiltonurbanblog.co.nz/2015/05/waikato-expressway-6-km-shorter-35-min-faster/#comment-4904 Hamilton Urban Blog 3 June 2015]</ref> A critic has said that the calculations do not take account of the costs of owning and operating a vehicle on the roads, nor rising fuel costs.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sunday-star-times/business/4366408/Going-down-the-wrong-road Sunday Star Times 21 November 2010]</ref> In 2016 some MPs were concerned Auckland congestion would cut travel time savings and hence the cost-benefit ratio of 1.4:1. One MP commented that the [[Waikato Connection#Potential reintroduction|alternative commuter train]], with the same CBR, didn\u2019t \"get a look in\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.nz/resource/en-NZ/51DBSCH_SCR68586_1/8d2e04c737dcf7edebb3c2d0a61cdf0513c4e2f2|title=2014/15 Annual Review of the Ministry of Transport and the New Zealand Transport Agency|last=|first=|date=11 February 2016|website=Report of the Transport and Industrial Relations Committee|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Future extension==\nAs of October 2017, the NZTA is investigating extending the Waikato Expressway south of Cambridge {{convert|16|km|abbr=on}} to the SH 1/SH 29 intersection at Piarere, bypassing the existing highway around the shores of [[Lake Karapiro]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Short-list of options for key State Highway 1 route through Waikato released |url= https://www.nzta.govt.nz/media-releases/short-list-of-options-for-key-state-highway-1-route-through-waikato-released/ |date= 20 October 2017 |publisher= NZTA}}</ref>\n\n==Exit list==\n{{